T1  - Conditional and unconditional statistical independence
AU  - Phillips, Peter C.B.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 38
IS  - 3
SP  - 341
EP  - 348
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90049-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900498
AB  - Conditional independence almost everywhere in the space of the conditioning variates does not imply unconditional independence, although it may well imply unconditional independence of certain functions of the variables. An example that is important in linear regression theory is discussed in detail. This involves orthogonal projections on random linear manifolds, which are conditionally independent but not unconditionally independent under normality. Necessary and sufficient conditions are obtained under which conditional independence does imply unconditional independence.
